"add"><CodeA name="rule" value="836643"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018577-20180323-194546"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/IGV KIS.XX N/EEC N/GEN N/PLT R/ASI R/EC R/EEU R/ENG R/EU R/FEO R/RS R/UK R/UR R/WEU </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday RUSSIA NERVE AGENT RUSSIA OLIGARCHS RUSSIA SPY RUSSIA U.K. SB126955385469309739639045841173111015500761 Abrahmsohn, Trevor Abramovich, Roman Blair, Tony Borodin, Andrei Cameron, David Chelsea Deripaska, Oleg Litvinenko, Alexander May, Theresa Murphy, Richard Putin, Vladimir Shaxson, Nicholas Stephens, Aaron Usmanov, Alisher SYND CODES_REVIEWED U.K. News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OUKN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">U.K. Ire at Russia Prompts Focus on London-Based Oligarchs; Prime minister's response to ex-spy's poisoning draws attention to capital city's standing as global showcase for Russian wealth</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>LONDONâ€”British Prime Minister Theresa May came out swinging last week after a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-russian-spy-poisoned-by-nerve-agent-u-k-police-say-1520447098">nerve-agent attack on a former spy</ELink> on British soil, expelling 23 Russian diplomats and saying the U.K. would "freeze Russian state assets" if they posed risks to the life or property of people in Britain.</Para><Para>Mrs. May didn't mention anything about imposing financial sanctions on Kremlin cronies, some of whom have made London the showplace of their wealth.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Russian money has permeated some of Britain's top institutions over the past two decades, though international sanctions and falling commodity prices have stemmed the flow of funds in recent years. Wealthy Russians have snapped up real-estate, taken stakes in two beloved soccer clubs, and bought one of the country's oldest newspapers.</Para><Para>Britain has historically taken a hands-off approach to financial regulation and London has benefited enormously as money from abroad has bolstered its legal, financial and real-estate industries.</Para><Para>The government has taken some measures to <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-to-crack-down-on-money-laundering-with-public-register-of-property-owners-1463081402">crack down on tax evasion and money laundering</ELink>, such as passing laws meant to make the ultimate owners of companies more transparent. Critics say these have amounted to more rhetoric than action.</Para><Para>Nicholas Shaxson, a financial investigator and author of a book on U.K.'s offshore industry, says London's role as a global money hub "has been a central plank of the British economy since the end of its empire," and that this month's poisoning was unlikely "to provoke a root-and-branch reform."</Para><Para>The Financial Secrecy Index, produced by the London-based advocacy group Tax Justice Network, said in a January report that the U.K., including its autonomous overseas territories and crown dependencies, ranks as the world's largest tax haven based on a combination of assets and opacity.</Para><Para>Almost one in 10 properties in London's central Westminster borough is owned by offshore companies, mostly from U.K. territories, according to Transparency International, an anticorruption organization. That includes a $60 million mansion in tony Belgrave Square that Oleg Deripaska, a Russian metals tycoon close to Russian President Vladimir Putin, bought through a British Virgin Islands company, according to disclosures he made to a U.K. court.</Para><Para>The Russian moguls who made their fortunes from the privatization of Soviet assets in the 1990s saw Britain as a safe place to shield their wealth from volatility in their homeland. For the new Russian elite, Britain offered unparalleled tax perks, a reliable court system, and a social milieu that let them play at aristocracy after decades of forced egalitarianism.</Para><Para>British officials lauded the flow as proof of Britain's attractiveness to foreign wealthâ€”though residents blamed it for pushing up property prices and suggesting that Britain courts corrupt wealth.</Para><Para>Russian billionaires set consecutive records for English house purchases, topping out so far with former Bank of Moscow President Andrei Borodin's Â£140 million mansion outside London. Energy and mining magnates Roman Abramovich and Alisher Usmanov projected their rivalries on to the soccer field, taking stakes in premier London clubs Chelsea and Arsenal respectively.</Para><Para>Mrs. May's predecessors, David Cameron and Tony Blair, came under fire for not going beyond token diplomatic moves to punish Mr. Putin and his inner circle for aggressive acts, such as the murder of former Russian spy Alexander Litvinenko in London. An inquiry found in 2016 that his <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-probably-approved-litvinenko-poisoning-says-u-k-inquiry-1453371335">poisoning was likely ordered by Mr. Putin</ELink>.</Para><Para>Mr. Cameron pledged to keep dirty money out in part by making ownership of assets more transparent through public registers. Since 2016, companies in the U.K. have had to report their ultimate owners, and starting in 2021, offshore companies buying U.K. properties will have to do the same. But activists say those laws should be implemented sooner and more strictly.</Para><Para>"We don't know who owns British companies, who uses British bank accounts and who owns British property, and the government deliberately isn't asking for that information," said Richard Murphy, a professor at City, University of London and a chartered accountant.</Para><Para>Mrs. May's biggest potential weapon against Mr. Putin's cronies are "unexplained wealth orders," which since just last month have given British authorities the power to freeze questionable assets, reversing the burden of proof onto the owner to show how they got money. The measures trace back to Mrs. May's initiative as interior minister in Mr. Cameron's government.</Para><Para>Such orders would be particularly effective for foreign officials whose income declarations don't match their families' lifestyles in the U.K. Last monthâ€”before Sergei Skripal and his daughter were poisoned on March 4â€”two such orders were <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://blogs.wsj.com/riskandcompliance/2018/03/01/the-morning-risk-report-u-k-brings-its-first-wealth-orders/">used to freeze two properties</ELink> worth a total of Â£22 million that the National Crime Agency said are owned by a "politically exposed person." The agency hasn't said where the person is from or given any further details.</Para><Para>Aaron Stephens, a partner at King &amp; Spalding, said such orders would face legal challenges, and judges will be wary of issuing them if they think they're being used by the government to score political points.</Para><Para>Going further in taking on Russian money by, for instance, expropriating oligarchs' mansions could scare other superrich from developing countries, said Trevor Abrahmsohn, of Glentree International, which dominates mansion sales in northwest London. Chinese and Arabs are the main foreign players in the city's property market now, according to estate agents and researchers from the London School of Economics.</Para><Para>"We have to be careful that we don't make these wealth creators so uncomfortable that we push them into the arms of our European neighbors," Mr. Abrahmsohn said. "We need these people to invest in this country. Even more so after Brexit."</Para><Para>Jenny Gross contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to Anatoly Kurmanaev at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Anatoly.kurmanaev@wsj.com">Anatoly.kurmanaev@wsj.com</ELink> and Margot Patrick at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:margot.patrick@wsj.com">margot.patrick@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Anatoly Kurmanaev and Margot Patrick </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-ire-at-russia-prompts-focus-on-london-based-oligarchs-1521798378" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

